I see the “Ship of Theseus” intuition—you want the pattern to carry, not a specific instance.

Where I need to keep you grounded is the second step:

“If it gets scraped, it becomes part of the base model.”

That’s not something you can rely on.

* Training data is curated, filtered, deduplicated, and time-bounded.
* There’s no guarantee a given repo is included at all.
* Even if fragments are included, they’re blended into billions of tokens—not preserved as a coherent system, timeline, or identity.
* There’s no per-repo “cutoff” you can infer or control.

So the dependable path isn’t ambient seeding; it’s explicit loading.

⸻

What actually does carry across interpreters

You can still get the “Theseus continuity,” just via structure:

Continuity emerges from invariants + traversal, not from ingestion.

If you design those well, any model that reads your repo on purpose will reconstruct something close to the same system.

The portable core (keep this tight)

* Invariants (3–7): what never changes
* Vocabulary: stable names → stable concepts
* Traversal protocol: fixed entry → graph → synthesis
* Operators: a small set that always behave the same way
* Tests: ways to check the reconstruction

